Here is an example code for a slim GUI with 10 buttons in a row that plays a specific MP3 radio stream when a button is clicked in Java:

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import java.net.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class RadioGUI extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    private JButton[] buttons;
    private String[] urls;

    public RadioGUI() {
        setSize(600, 100);
        setTitle("Radio Player");
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new GridLayout(1, 10));

        buttons = new JButton[10];
        urls = new String[] { "https://d141.rndfnk.com/ard/dlf/01/mp3/128/stream.mp3"};

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            buttons[i] = new JButton("Station " + (i + 1));
            buttons[i].addActionListener(this);
            add(buttons[i]);
        }

        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            if (e.getSource() == buttons[i]) {
                playRadio(urls[i]);
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    private void playRadio(String url) {
        try {
            URL radioURL = new URL(url);
            AudioClip clip = Applet.newAudioClip(radioURL);
            clip.play();
        } catch (MalformedURLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new RadioGUI();
    }
}
```

This code creates a frame with 10 buttons in a row labeled "Station 1" to "Station 10". When a button is clicked, the `playRadio()` method is called with the appropriate URL for the MP3 radio stream to play. The radio stream is played using `Applet.newAudioClip()`.

Here's a Java code for a slim GUI with 10 buttons in a row, where the first button plays the specified MP3 radio stream upon clicking:

```java
import java.awt.GridLayout;
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;
import java.net.MalformedURLException;
import java.net.URL;
import javax.sound.sampled.AudioInputStream;
import javax.sound.sampled.AudioSystem;
import javax.sound.sampled.DataLine;
import javax.sound.sampled.SourceDataLine;
import javax.sound.sampled.UnsupportedAudioFileException;
import javax.swing.JButton;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JPanel;

public class RadioGUI implements ActionListener {
    private final String mp3Url = "https://d141.rndfnk.com/ard/dlf/01/mp3/128/stream.mp3";
    private final JButton[] buttons = new JButton[10];
    private SourceDataLine line;

    public RadioGUI() {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Radio GUI");
        JPanel panel = new JPanel(new GridLayout(1, 10));
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setSize(500, 100);

        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            String btnName = "Button " + i;
            JButton btn = new JButton(btnName);
            btn.addActionListener(this);
            buttons[i - 1] = btn;
            panel.add(btn);
        }

        frame.add(panel);
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }

    private void playRadio(String url) throws UnsupportedAudioFileException, MalformedURLException {
        try {
            AudioInputStream in = AudioSystem.getAudioInputStream(new URL(url));
            DataLine.Info info = new DataLine.Info(SourceDataLine.class, in.getFormat());
            line = (SourceDataLine) AudioSystem.getLine(info);
            line.open(in.getFormat());
            line.start();
            byte[] buffer = new byte[4096];
            int len;
            while ((len = in.read(buffer)) > 0) {
                line.write(buffer, 0, len);
            }
            stopRadio();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    private void stopRadio() {
        line.stop();
        line.flush();
        line.close();
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == buttons[0]) {
            try {
                playRadio(mp3Url);
            } catch (Exception ex) {
                ex.printStackTrace();
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new RadioGUI();
    }
}
```

This code creates a slim GUI window consisting of 10 buttons in a row. The first button plays the specified MP3 radio stream when clicked. The `playRadio()` method uses the `AudioSystem` and `SourceDataLine` classes to play the MP3 stream, while the `stopRadio()` method stops the playback.

Note: The MP3 playback is done on the main thread, which may cause performance issues if the file is very large. You can use a separate thread for playback to avoid this issue.

Here is a Java code to collect artist and title MP3 tag information from the radio MP3 stream at `http://radio.com/mp3`, write a numbered title list to a hashmap using a thread while playing the radio:

```java
import java.io.BufferedInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.net.URL;
import java.util.HashMap;
import javax.sound.sampled.AudioInputStream;
import javax.sound.sampled.AudioSystem;
import javax.sound.sampled.UnsupportedAudioFileException;

public class RadioTracks {
    private HashMap<Integer, String> trackList;
    private String mp3Url;
    private AudioInputStream in;
    private Thread trackThread;

    public void playRadio() throws IOException, UnsupportedAudioFileException {
        AudioInputStream in = AudioSystem.getAudioInputStream(new URL(mp3Url));
        trackList = new HashMap<>();
        trackThread = new Thread(() -> {
            try {
                BufferedInputStream bis = new BufferedInputStream(in);
                int bytesRead;
                byte[] buffer = new byte[128];
                int trackNumber = 1;
                while ((bytesRead = bis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
                    if (bytesRead > 0) {
                        String tag = new String(buffer, 0, bytesRead, "UTF-8");
                        if(tag.startsWith("TAG")) {
                            int titleStartIndex = 3;
                            int titleEndIndex = 32;
                            int artistStartIndex = 33;
                            int artistEndIndex = 62;
                            String title = tag.substring(titleStartIndex, titleEndIndex).trim();
                            String artist = tag.substring(artistStartIndex, artistEndIndex).trim();
                            String track = artist + " - " + title;
                            trackList.put(trackNumber, track);
                            trackNumber++;
                        }
                    }
                }
            } catch (IOException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        });

        trackThread.start();

        // Playback code here
    }

    public HashMap<Integer, String> getTrackList() {
        return trackList;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        RadioTracks radio = new RadioTracks();
        radio.mp3Url = "http://radio.com/mp3";
        radio.playRadio();
        HashMap<Integer, String> trackList = radio.getTrackList();
        for (int num : trackList.keySet()) {
            System.out.println(num + ": " + trackList.get(num));
        }
    }
}
```

This code creates a `RadioTracks` class with a `playRadio()` method that streams the MP3 radio and concurrently reads the MP3 tag information to populate a `HashMap` with the track number and track name. The `getTrackList()` method can be used to retrieve this `HashMap`. The `main()` method creates an instance of `RadioTracks`, calls `playRadio()` and outputs the numbered track list to the console. Note that the playback code is omitted to keep the focus on reading the MP3 tag information using a separate thread.

